Code review ranks just behind design review in value (cost/time savings). In fact code reviews are so beneficial that if I was working on a solo project I would either pay for them to be done or review the code myself after a suitable cooling off period, depending on what I was working on.<p>On the other hand, I have also witnessed sloppy, lazy code reviews that catch nothing except the occasional typo. This amounts to an unjustifiable waste of time. Fortunately, it is easy to tell a good code reviews from bad by tracking defect discovery and digging into review comments as needed.<p>One thing that code review catches that <i>nothing else does</i> is code that is poorly written but functional (i.e. passing tests).<p>The example I always trot out is<p><pre><code>    for ( int i=0 ; i < this.MyControl.TabPages.Count ; i++ )
    {
       this.MyControl.TabPages.Remove ( this.MyControl.TabPages[i] );
       i--;
    }
</code></pre>
This code works according to spec, passes all the tests, but is bordering on unmaintainable. At best it&#x27;s a WTF.<p>(Written up here: <a href="http://cvmountain.com/2011/09/whats-wrong-with-this-code-really/" rel="nofollow">http://cvmountain.com/2011/09/whats-wrong-with-this-code-rea...</a>)

> Perhaps you could give an example of yield as an expression? &quot;x = x + yield&quot; doesn&#x27;t make a lot of sense to me.<p>And yet it&#x27;s perfectly valid. ES6 generators are (shallow) coroutines (or &quot;extended generators&quot; in Python-land[0]). From the outside, they provide a `send()` method as the converse to `next()`, and that method is used to inject a value back in the generator, via `yield` as an expression. And yes you can use the same yield to send a value out and retrieve one in the same &quot;yield step&quot;.<p>That is how e.g. taskjs[1] works:<p><pre><code>    spawn(function*() {
        var data = yield $.ajax(url);
        $(&#x27;#result&#x27;).html(data);
        var status = $(&#x27;#status&#x27;).html(&#x27;Download complete.&#x27;);
        yield status.fadeIn().promise();
        yield sleep(2000);
        status.fadeOut();
    });
</code></pre>
the first line sends a promise to the scheduler and suspends the generator, the scheduler then resumes the generator with send() to inject the resolution of the promise back in.<p>> The meaning of a symbol can often be inferred from its context - it doesn&#x27;t need to be a reserved word.<p>Not without function * . the purpose of function * is precisely to provide the context for `yield` being not-a-name.<p>> Yes, it would not be allowable to have an open paren after yield.<p>You do realize how utterly insane that reads right? You propose crippling `yield` and making it significantly less convenient and sensible to get rid function * (and the colon does not work, it conflicts with labels)<p>[0] <a href="http://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0342/" rel="nofollow">http://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0342/</a><p>[1] <a href="http://taskjs.org/" rel="nofollow">http://taskjs.org/</a>
